			<Body>
				<Text Type="text">
					&lt;p&gt;I'm not a massive fan of Bailey's myself, but do love a chocolate mousse. Since unless you're going way overboard with the alcohol, you're not really going to disrupt the mousse and make it soupy, you can use anything that &lt;strong&gt;you&lt;/strong&gt; think goes with chocolate. Personally, I love the following paired with a good &lt;strong&gt;dark&lt;/strong&gt; chocolate:&lt;/p&gt;

					&lt;ul&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;Kahlua/Tia Maria (most similar in spirit to Bailey's)&lt;/li&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;Port or madeira&lt;/li&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;Deep but not too peaty Scotch &lt;/li&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;Dark rum (I'd leave the &lt;a href="http://www.stroh.at/en/products/stroh-original/" rel="noreferrer"&gt;continental "rums"&lt;/a&gt; to fruit desserts, where they excel)&lt;/li&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;Brandy&lt;/li&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;Kirsch&lt;/li&gt;
					&lt;/ul&gt;

					&lt;p&gt;I'd avoid lighter or delicate / floral spirits, since they don't really work (for me) with a deep dark chocolate.&lt;/p&gt;

					&lt;p&gt;I'd keep it to under about a shot per cup to avoid thinning the mousse too much. And please try a &lt;em&gt;tiny&lt;/em&gt; pinch of salt, which the original recipe is missing but is essential for a good chocolate dessert!&lt;/p&gt;

				</Text>
			</Body>
